  "prompt": "How do I deal with a person that tells the same divorce story from 30 years ago over and over?",
  "response": "Here are some strategies to handle someone who repeatedly tells the same divorce story:\n\n1. Compassionate approaches:\n- Listen briefly and empathize\n- Gently acknowledge their feelings\n- Redirect the conversation after a short time\n\n2. Conversational techniques:\n- Ask if they'd like to talk about something else\n- Change the subject proactively\n- Use body language to signal you're less engaged\n\n3. Direct communication:\n- Kindly explain that you've heard the story before\n- Set boundaries about how often you want to discuss it\n- Suggest they might benefit from talking to a counselor\n\n4. Supportive suggestions:\n- Encourage them to write their story down\n- Suggest journaling or memoir writing\n- Recommend support groups for divorce recovery\n\n5. Professional help:\n- If repetitive storytelling is excessive, they might benefit from:\n- Grief counseling\n- Therapy\n- Mental health evaluation\n\n6. Patience and understanding:\n- Recognize they might be processing old trauma\n- Be kind, even if the story is repetitive\n- Remember this might be their way of healing\n\n7. Last resort:\n- Politely excuse yourself\n- Limit conversation time\n- Minimize interactions if necessary\n\nChoose approaches based on your relationship and the person's personality.",
